<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1229,2002]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1229,1255]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species is the only species in 
<taxonomicName box="[694,849,1229,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Nyctiophylax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[694,849,1229,1254]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Nyctiophylax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(s.str.) having an open forewing median cell. The species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Brauer" authorityName="Brauer" authorityYear="1865" box="[457,730,1266,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Nyctiophylax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinensis" subGenus="Nyctiophylax">
<emphasis box="[457,640,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">N. (N.) sinensis</emphasis>
Brauer
</taxonomicName>
, from which it is distinguished by having cerci divided into lobes and sternite IX with posterior margin straight and vertical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1229,2002]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,351,1341,1367]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Description:</emphasis>
Male. Body uniformly pale brown. Maxillary palp formula (I,II)-IV-III-V. Forewing length 4.0 mm. Median cell on forewings open.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1229,2002]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
Male genitalia. Abdominal segment IX composed of robust, sclerotized sternite, nearly triangular, about 2 times higher than long, posterior margin straight and vertical in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1136,1453,1479]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–68" captionStartId="41.[151,270,1476,1500]" captionTargetBox="[202,1378,454,1455]" captionTargetId="figure-267@41.[194,1393,447,1466]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 64–68. Nyctiophylax (Nyctiophylax) hotay, new species, holotype. 64—genitalia, left lateral; 65—genitalia, dorsal; 66 —gonopods, ventral; 67—phallic apparatus, left lateral; 68—phallic apparatus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361548/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
); tergum IX indiscernible as membranous integument above sternite IX and behind segment X. Segment X semisclerotized, setose, elongate, connected to dorsal angles of sternite IX (
<figureCitation box="[777,868,1528,1554]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–68" captionStartId="41.[151,270,1476,1500]" captionTargetBox="[202,1378,454,1455]" captionTargetId="figure-267@41.[194,1393,447,1466]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 64–68. Nyctiophylax (Nyctiophylax) hotay, new species, holotype. 64—genitalia, left lateral; 65—genitalia, dorsal; 66 —gonopods, ventral; 67—phallic apparatus, left lateral; 68—phallic apparatus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361548/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
); deeply incised, producing large quadrangular dorsal interlobular gap with rod-like lateral lobes in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[921,1009,1565,1591]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–68" captionStartId="41.[151,270,1476,1500]" captionTargetBox="[202,1378,454,1455]" captionTargetId="figure-267@41.[194,1393,447,1466]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 64–68. Nyctiophylax (Nyctiophylax) hotay, new species, holotype. 64—genitalia, left lateral; 65—genitalia, dorsal; 66 —gonopods, ventral; 67—phallic apparatus, left lateral; 68—phallic apparatus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361548/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
). Cerci large, long, tall, setose, each divided into 1 dorsal, 2 apical and 1 ventral lobes in lateral view. Paraproctal complexes each consisting of 2 paraproctal processes; 1 dorsally arching spine originating anteriorly, 1 starting from its fulcrum (meeting point of sternite IX, cercus and segment X) and running almost vertically ventrad to end between bases of gonopods. Gonopods robust, oriented almost horizontally, elongate, basal part sinuous. Phallic apparatus (
<figureCitation box="[159,300,1752,1778]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–68" captionStartId="41.[151,270,1476,1500]" captionTargetBox="[202,1378,454,1455]" captionTargetId="figure-267@41.[194,1393,447,1466]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 64–68. Nyctiophylax (Nyctiophylax) hotay, new species, holotype. 64—genitalia, left lateral; 65—genitalia, dorsal; 66 —gonopods, ventral; 67—phallic apparatus, left lateral; 68—phallic apparatus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361548/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figs. 67, 68</figureCitation>
) located dorsally in genitalia, guided by spine-like, long paraproctal processes; phallic apparatus with tube-shaped, sclerotized phallotheca continuing into membranous endotheca (or endophallus) with pair of sclerites on retracted membranes, these sclerites ending in laterad-directed, spiny apices in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[159,247,1864,1890]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–68" captionStartId="41.[151,270,1476,1500]" captionTargetBox="[202,1378,454,1455]" captionTargetId="figure-267@41.[194,1393,447,1466]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 64–68. Nyctiophylax (Nyctiophylax) hotay, new species, holotype. 64—genitalia, left lateral; 65—genitalia, dorsal; 66 —gonopods, ventral; 67—phallic apparatus, left lateral; 68—phallic apparatus, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361548/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
